

# URL Shortener — Go + Fiber + GORM + PostgreSQL

A production-ready URL shortener built with Fiber (the fastest Go HTTP framework).

---

## Why Fiber?

| Feature | Fiber | Gin |
|---------|-------|-----|
| HTTP engine | fasthttp (custom) | net/http (standard) |
| Requests/sec | ~300k+ | ~150k+ |
| API style | Express.js-like | Rails-like |
| Memory usage | Very low | Low |

Fiber uses `fasthttp` under the hood which avoids many allocations that
Go's standard `net/http` makes. Great choice for high-traffic services.

---

## Project Structure

```
urlshortener/
├── cmd/
│   └── main.go                     ← entry point, wires all layers together
├── internal/
│   ├── config/
│   │   └── config.go               ← reads .env / environment variables
│   ├── database/
│   │   └── database.go             ← PostgreSQL connection + migrations
│   ├── models/
│   │   └── url.go                  ← GORM model (maps to "urls" table)
│   ├── repository/
│   │   └── url_repository.go       ← all DB queries, nothing else
│   ├── service/
│   │   └── url_service.go          ← all business logic, nothing else
│   └── handlers/
│       └── url_handler.go          ← Fiber handlers (HTTP layer only)
├── .env.example                    ← copy to .env and fill in values
├── go.mod
└── README.md
```

### Layer Responsibilities

```
config      → knows about environment variables only
database    → knows about PostgreSQL connection only
models      → knows about data shape only
repository  → knows about database queries only
service     → knows about business rules only  (no HTTP!)
handlers    → knows about HTTP only            (no business logic!)
main        → wires everything together
```

---

## Quick Start

### Prerequisites
- Go 1.22 or later
- PostgreSQL 14 or later

### Steps

```bash
# 1. Set up your config
cp .env.example .env
# Edit .env — set your DB_DSN with your postgres password

# 2. Create the PostgreSQL database
psql -U postgres -c "CREATE DATABASE urlshortener;"

# 3. Install Go dependencies
go mod tidy

# 4. Run the server (GORM auto-creates the table on first run)
go run cmd/main.go
```

You should see:
```
✅ PostgreSQL connected
🔄 Running database migrations...
✅ Migrations complete
🌐 Listening on http://localhost:3000
```

